32. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2023385908
T1  - Evaluation of Hormonal Profile and Clinical Features among Adolescent Girls with Unilateral Polycystic Ovarian Morphology (PCOM)
A1  - Abdel Wahed R.M.
A1  - Fathiagaba N.
A1  - Elsheikh A. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Background:The most prevalent endocrine condition in women of reproductive age is polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS). Varying ethnic and racial groupings have different clinical characteristic frequencies, start times, and severity levels. Despite the fact that PCOS significantly worsens metabolic, endocrine, and reproductive health. It is possible that PCOS is a primary ovarian condition if unilateral PCO exists. Aim of the Work: To detect the correlation between the unilateral polycystic ovarian morphology and clinical presentations and hormonal profile of girls with unilateral PCOM. Patients and Methods: Observational research was conducted at Al Zahraa University Hospital, Department of Obstetrics and Gynecology, through the period from December 2020 to September 2021 on 53 girls with unilateral polycystic ovarian morphology (PCOM) confirmed by ultrasound. To rule out additional conditions that resemble these PCOS-like clinical symptoms, information regarding clinical features, related illnesses, family history, hormone levels, and ultrasonography were gathered for all patients. Result(s): The present study revealed that the mean ovarian volume of PCO had substantial negative connection with FSH and substantial positive connection with LH/FSH ratio, and prolactin hormone. The mean follicles number per ovary (FNPO) of PCO had substantial positive connection with LH, LH/FSH ratio, and AMH. There was statistically substantial increase in E2 (pg/mL) hormone and AMH (ng/mL) in girls with unilateral PCO. Conclusion(s): We propose that Unilateral PCOM that diagnosed accidentally during ultrasound examination may have no impacts on clinical presentations or hormonal profile, thus the presence of unilateral PCOM may be primarily an ovarian disorder.Copyright © 2022, Anka Publishers. All rights reserved.
