53. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2022055679
T1  - Vitamin D Deficiency and Metabolic Syndrome in Polycystic Ovarian Disorder (Pcod) Patients along with Anti-Mullerian Hormone Levels
A1  - Raj M.
A1  - Kulshreshtha R.
A1  - Bansal P.
A1  - Yadav K.
A1  - Kansal R. 
Y1  - 2022//
N2  - Introdution: Vitamin D supplementation is a known pharmaceutical intervention in many lifestyles related and metabolic disorders. This study was designed to assess the status of Vitamin D in relation to metabolic syndrome and Anti-Mullerian Hormone (AMH, marker of disease severity) levels in PCOD patients in a rural area of Haryana to assess potential for possible Vitamin D supplementation. Method(s): The case control study included 50 PCOD patients (Rotterdam criteria) and 50 age matched healthy controls. Clinical examination, anthropometry, lipid profile, fasting glucose, HbA1c, vitamin D and AMH levels were performed in all enrolled subjects. Result(s): BMI, waist circumference, fasting glucose, HbA1c, triglycerides, total cholesterol, LDL-cholesterol and prevalence of dyslipidemia were significantly higher in study than in control group subjects. Metabolic syndrome was diagnosed in 17 patients of PCOD (34%). Vitamin D levels were significantly lower in PCOD patients (18.10+/-13.29 vs 24.10+/-12.36 ng/mL, p=0.002). 72% of PCOD patients had Vitamin D deficiency (Vitamin D < 20 ng/mL) as compared to 36% of healthy controls (p<0.001). Vitamin D levels were significantly lower in PCOD patients with metabolic syndrome compared to those without metabolic syndrome (12.6+/-4.71 vs 20.9+/-15.32 ng/mL, p=0.040). Vitamin D levels were inversely correlated with AMH levels in PCOD. Conclusion(s): Vitamin D deficiency correlated with severity of PCOD and was most severe in the patients with PCOD and metabolic syndrome. Assessment of vitamin D levels may be helpful, especially in PCOD patients with metabolic syndrome suggesting possible benefit of vitamin D supplementation.Copyright © 2022 Wolters Kluwer Medknow Publications. All rights reserved.
