214. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2014593657
T1  - Relationship between serum Prolactin level and polycystic ovary syndrome in the context of its disease parameters in Korean women
A1  - Lee H.J.
A1  - Jo H.
A1  - Lee S.Y.
A1  - Joo J.K. 
Y1  - 2021//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: To investigate the incidence and the causes of hyperprolactinemia in Korean polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) patients and compare their physiologic and clinical parameters. STUDY DESIGN: A total of 140 PCOS patients in a single center setting were included. PCOS was diagnosed according to the criteria of the Rotterdam consensus, and hyperprolactinemia was diagnosed with 2 consecutive blood tests with elevated serum prolactin level. Laboratory tests including serum follicle-stimulating hormone, luteinizing hormone, thyroid-stimulating hormone, anti-Mullerian hormone, prolactin, total and free testosterones, dehydroepiandrosterone sulfate, 17alpha-hydroxyprogesterone, HbA1c, and fasting glucose were conducted. RESULT(S): Among 140 PCOS patients, 16 showed elevated prolactin level (39.72+/-15.62 ng/mL); 3 patients were diagnosed with medication-associated causes, and 4 patients were diagnosed with pituitary lesions by brain magnetic resonance imaging. In the hyperprolactinemia group the mean of HbA1c level was significantly lower than that in the normal prolactin group. The clinical parameters of PCOS suggesting hyperandrogenism, such as hirsutism, acne, alopecia, and irregular menstruation were not significantly different between the 2 groups. CONCLUSION(S): According to our study, PCOS and hyperprolactinemia are independent disorders with frequent comorbidity, rather a close causal relationship.Copyright © Journal of Reproductive Medicine Inc.
