325. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2010513777
T1  - MOLECULAR STUDY OF LH-RECEPTOR GENE POLYMORPHISMS AND ITS ASSOCIATION WITH ANTI-MULLERIAN HORMONE IN POLYCYSTIC OVARIAN SYNDROME OF IRAQI WOMEN
A1  - Al-Lami H.B.
A1  - Al-Tu'ma F.J.
A1  - Al-Tu'ma A.F. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - Polycystic ovary syndrome is a metabolic disturbance that has features of multiple hormonal imbalances that produce short and long-term consequences on women's health. It is now categorized as the most common pathology of the endocrine system in females at reproductive age with principle features of menstrual irregularity (amenorrhea, oligomenorrhea) and elevated androgens (acne, hirsutism). The luteinizing hormone receptor (LHR) mediates actions of luteinizing hormone (LH), which together with follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) constitutes the two key pituitary gonadotropins for regulating ovarian function. Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH) is considered to be a potentially important biomarker of the reproductive potential of cattle. It is a growth factor, produced from the granulosa cells of the ovary and Sertoli cells of testes, and was first discovered to play an important role in sex differentiation in fetal life. The current study aimed to investigate the role of LH receptor genes polymorphisms in the development of the polycystic ovarian syndrome and its association with Anti-Mullerian hormone, LH, FSH and other biomarkers in Iraqi patients. Material(s) and Method(s): The subjects of the current study involved 100 women with ages ranged between (18-37) years during the period from Dec. 2019 to June 2020. These subjects include 50 cases of a polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) obtained from a gynecological and obstetric teaching hospital, Kerbala health directorate, Kerbala, Iraq and another 50 healthy women as a control group. Each of LH, FSH, and AMH levels were determined by the chemiluminescent automates immunoassay system (Cobas e411, Roche diagnostics, Germany). Gene polymorphism of the LH receptor gene was performed by real-time polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR). The results obtained showed a significant increase in each of the luteinizing hormone (LH), and Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH) in women with PCOS (P< 0.05) as compared with control groups of all age and BMI. Molecular analysis of the LH receptor gene detects LHB gene polymorphisms (rs5030774) in heterozygous mutant genotypes (G/A) in the 13/50 patient group (26%), while no one was observed in the control group. Homozygotes (A/A) was observed only in control 3/50 (6%) and the normal wild type (GG) genotypes found 37/50 (74%) and 47/50 (94%) in both patient and control groups respectively. Whilst LHCGR gene A/A found only in 1/50 in control (2%) and G/C was found in the patient only 8/50 (16%) while G/G genotype was also found in patients 42/50 (84%) as compared with the control group 49/50 (98%). Anti-Mullerian Hormone (AMH) and LH levels in PCOS women were significantly increased in PCOS women, while a non-significant difference inFSH values was obtained as compared with control groups. The study population has mutant in homozygous and heterozygous of LHB and LHCGR genes polymorphisms (rs5030774 and 121912520) respectively, it can be argued that these variant LH proteins have little or no impact on the phenotype of the PCOS population.Copyright © 2020. All Rights Reserved.
