326. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2010513711
T1  - THE LINK BETWEEN SERUM PARAOXONASE ACTIVITY AND PREGNANCY OUTCOMES IN IRAQI WOMEN UNDERGOING IVF/ICSI
A1  - Ahmed M.A.K.
A1  - Wadood S.A.
A1  - Mahdi Q.A. 
Y1  - 2020//
N2  - The impact of oxidative stress on in vitro fertilization was confirmed by many researchers. The goal of this study was to explore the link between serum Paraoxonase activity (PON1) and chemical pregnancy (CP) in women undergoing in vitro fertilization. Ninety-nine infertile women who underwent IVF treatment using multi agonist protocol were included in this study. Their ages range from 22 to 38 years. The research participants were grouped according to infertility reason into: male cause of infertility (control group; n = 25), poly cystic ovary syndrome females (PCOS; n = 21), low AMH females (n = 26) and unexplained infertility females (UI group; n = 27). Two PON1 enzymes activities were assessed; paraoxonase (Basal and salt stimulated s-s) and arylesterase activities. The mean levels of serum PON1 activities (Basal, S-S) of PCOS and low AMH groups showed significant (P<0.05) increase when compared with that of control and UI groups, mean of serum arylesterase activity of UI, PCOS and low AMH groups showed significant (P<0.05) increase when compared with that of control group. During IVF process, ovarian stimulation resulted in increased oxidative stress and increase activity of PON1 in PCOS and low AMH groups. Higher PON1 activity was found in non-pregnant women with PCOS than pregnant women.Copyright © 2020. All Rights Reserved.
