394. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 2003262393
T1  - Is antimullerian hormone a true ovarian marker for fibroid, polycystic ovary syndrome and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism in infertile women?
A1  - Farooq B.
A1  - Jahan S.
A1  - Ara J.
A1  - Ghani U.
A1  - Malik A.
A1  - Abbasi S. 
Y1  - 2019//
N2  - Objective: To measure Anti mullerian Hormone (AMH) concentration as a true ovarian marker in polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS), fibroids and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism (HH). Methodology: This study was a prospective comparative trial conducted from January to November 2014 at Department of Animal science, Quaid-e-Azam University in collaboration with Salma & Kafeel Medical Center, Islamabad, Pakistan. A total of 128 females were enrolled in the study. Result(s): Significant increase (P<0.001) of AMH concentration in PCOS was observed. Whereas significant decrease (P<0.05, P<0.01) was found in fibroids and hypogonadotropic hypogonadism, respectively. Significant negative correlation between AMH and Luteinizing Hormone (LH), Follicle Stimulating Hormone (FSH), prolactin (R=-1, P<0.001; R=-1, P< 0.001 and R=-1, P<0.01, respectively) was observed in Hypogonadotropic Hypogonadism (HH). High Significant negative correlation between AMH and prolactin (R =-1, P<0.001) was also observed in fibroids. Conclusion(s): AMH is a true ovarian marker in PCOS, fibroids and Hypogonadotropic Hypogonadism infertile female patients and it is a reproductive tool to measure infertility.Copyright © 2019, Pakistan Medical Association. All rights reserved.
